{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_1780196774151_24qod07mo41","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-4.7-opus","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" Looking at a 23-year-old male patient with acute simple gastritis triggered by spicy food, presenting with upper abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting over the past two days.\n\nThe clinical picture is straightforward: dietary indiscretion (spicy hotpot plus cold beer) causing mucosal irritation. Labs are reassuring with normal WBC and no signs of infection, vitals are stable, and physical exam shows only epigastric tenderness without peritoneal signs. My treatment approach centers on a PPI like omeprazole for acid suppression over a week, an antiemetic such as domperidone to address the nausea and vomiting, and a mucosal protectant like hydrotalcite or teprenone. I'm avoiding antibiotics since there's no evidence of infection and NSAIDs would only worsen the gastric irritation. Given his young age and lack of comorbidities, he should respond well to conservative management.\n\nFor recovery, I'm emphasizing bland diet, small frequent meals, adequate rest, and warm fluids while steering clear of spicy foods, alcohol, caffeine, and tea. I'll have him watch for alarm symptoms like hematemesis, melena, severe pain, or fever, and return in a few days if symptoms don't improve. Let me verify the medication availability on the national formulary to ensure these agents are covered.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":32312,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cd3af719-3dd0-488d-b07c-7e0e86da54e7","uuid":"4883e1d0-b431-4700-9b7e-68e48ad2624e"}
